    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Very small dolls made of bits of cloth, bone, and wood generally produced in Guatemala but probably having originated in the Maya culture utilizing scraps of fabric left over from making clothing. Children and adults confide their worries or troubles to the doll, and it is believed that the doll takes on the troubles so that the user can sleep in peace.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047871/Worry Dolls, BBC [online] (2006)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Zeer kleine poppetjes gemaakt van stof, been en hout waarbij restjes stof uit kledingateliers worden gebruikt. Kinderen en volwassenen vertellen hun problemen aan het poppetje, waarna het de problemen zou overnemen zodat de gebruiker rustig kan slapen. Zijn doorgaans uit Guatemala afkomstig, maar hebben hun oorsprong vermoedelijk in de Mayacultuur.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Sehr kleine Puppe, die aus Stücken von Kleidung, Knochen und Holz in der Regel in Guatemala gefertigt wird, aber ihre Ursprünge wahrscheinlich in der Maya-Kultur hat, die Stoffreste nutzte, die vom Kleidernähen übrig waren. Kinder und Erwachsene vertrauen der Puppe ihre Sorgen und Probleme an und man glaubt, dass die Puppe die Probleme annimmt und ihr Besitzer in Frieden schlafen kann.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種極小型的人偶，以布料、骨頭和木頭製成，通常製於瓜地馬拉，但可能源於馬雅文化，使用製衣剩下的布料加以製作。據說人偶可以幫忙分擔憂愁，所以大人小孩向人偶抒發心事或煩惱之後，即可安心入睡。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bonecas muito pequenas feitas de pedaços pequenos de pano, osso e madeira, geralmente produzidas na Guatemala, mas provavelmente originadas na cultura Maia, utilizando sobras de tecido de roupas. Crianças e adultos confiam suas preocupações ou problemas às bonecas; acredita-se que as bonecas assumem tais problemas, de modo que o usuário durma em paz.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000179/VP-intern</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000110648/Portuguese Translation Intern Project (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
